A user who has `write:admin` in one Keycloak realm can call the Manager API to update **Keycloak realm roles** for users in **another** realm, including **`master`**. The handler uses the `{realm}` path segment when talking to the identity provider but does not check that the caller may administer that realm. This could result in a privilege escalation to `master` realm administrator if the attacker controls any user in `master` realm.

### Details
In `manager/src/main/java/org/openremote/manager/security/UserResourceImpl.java`, there is no check to validate if the caller should be able to administer a realm they're trying to update.

```340:353:manager/src/main/java/org/openremote/manager/security/UserResourceImpl.java
    @Override
    public void updateUserRealmRoles(RequestParams requestParams, String realm, String userId, String[] roles) {
        try {
            identityService.getIdentityProvider().updateUserRealmRoles(
                realm,
                userId,
                roles);
        } catch (ClientErrorException ex) {
            ex.printStackTrace(System.out);
            throw new WebApplicationException(ex.getCause(), ex.getResponse().getStatus());
        } catch (Exception ex) {
            throw new WebApplicationException(ex);
        }
    }
```

### PoC
1. Create a **new** Keycloak realm other than `master`. Add a user and grant that user the OpenRemote client role `write:admin`. Remember the realm name (call it `NEW_REALM`).
2. In Keycloak realm `master`, pick a **low-privilege** user (no `admin` realm role). Copy that user’s UUID (`<master-user-uuid>`).
3. Authenticate as the user from step 1 and obtain a Bearer access token (`<token>`) for `NEW_REALM`.
4. Replace placeholders and run:
```bash
curl -k -X PUT "https://<host>/api/<NEW_REALM>/user/master/userRealmRoles/<master-user-uuid>" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer <token>" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '["admin"]'
```
5. In the Keycloak Admin Console, realm master, that user, Role mapping. Confirm the admin realm role is assigned.
### Impact
An attacker with the OpenRemote client role write:admin in any realm can call this API with {realm} set to another realm (for example master) and change Keycloak realm roles for users there. That can grant admin on master to a user UUID they target, which gives Keycloak administrator access for the master realm.", "epss": {"percentage": 0.00285, "percentile": 0.20051}, "ghsa_id": "GHSA-49vv-25qx-mg44", "github_reviewed_at": "2026-04-22T14:38:23Z", "html_url": "https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-49vv-25qx-mg44", "identifiers": [{"type": "GHSA", "value": "GHSA-49vv-25qx-mg44"}, {"type": "CVE", "value": "CVE-2026-41166"}], "nvd_published_at": "2026-04-22T21:17:09Z", "published_at": "2026-04-22T14:38:23Z", "references": ["https://github.com/openremote/openremote/security/advisories/GHSA-49vv-25qx-mg44", "https://github.com/openremote/openremote/releases/tag/1.22.1", "https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2026-41166", "https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-49vv-25qx-mg44"], "repository_advisory_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/openremote/openremote/security-advisories/GHSA-49vv-25qx-mg44", "severity": "high", "source_code_location": "https://github.com/openremote/openremote", "summary": "OpenRemote has Improper Access Control via updateUserRealmRoles function", "type": "reviewed", "updated_at": "2026-04-27T16:23:03Z", "url": "https://api.github.com/advisories/GHSA-49vv-25qx-mg44", "vulnerabilities": [{"first_patched_version": "1.22.1", "package": {"ecosystem": "maven", "name": "io.openremote:openremote-manager"}, "vulnerable_functions": [], "vulnerable_version_range": "< 1.22.1"}], "withdrawn_at": null}
